2.7 	We recommended and the Management agreed to direct the:
OIC, Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the Municipal Engineer in determining the status of projects recorded under the CIP accounts;
OIC, Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary adjusting entries for the reclassification of the completed projects from CIP accounts to the appropriate PPE accounts and to recognize the corresponding depreciation;
OIC, Municipal Accountant and Municipal Engineer to reconcile their records regularly to determine the status and correct balances of the CIP and PPE accounts; and
OIC, Municipal Accountant to henceforth, reclassify the projects recorded under the CIP to its proper PPE account upon its completion.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to undertake the following actions:

Direct the OIC - Municipal Accountant to strictly comply with documentary requirements by securing MOA/Trust Agreements and approved project proposals to form part of supporting documents depending on the nature of transaction in the implementation and liquidation of fund transfers as provided in Section 3.1.2 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012;

Require the Local Finance Committee to timely post the required reports in the utilization of funds received from the National Government for the implementation of programs, projects and activities. Further, these reports should be duly sent to oversight bodies and other offices where the submission of reports is required under existing laws, rules and regulations;

Instruct the Acting Municipal Treasurer to immediately return the amount of ₱44,120.00 representing unexpended balances of the fund transfers to the Bureau of the Treasury; and

Require the MSWDO to submit the documentary evidences to establish the legal identities of all the recipients of cash assistance, and qualifying documents to determine their eligibility thereto.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to:

Require the OIC-Municipal Accountant to individually verify and validate the SL account balances relating to the fund transfers to establish obligations therefrom and effect the necessary adjusting journal entries, if warranted. Balances should be reconciled with source agencies and valid amounts shall be duly returned thereto;

Ensure that MOA shall be secured first as required under COA Circular No. 94-013, before undertaking projects involving inter-agency fund transfers;

Direct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to initiate the filing of write-off for undocumented dormant accounts taking into consideration the requirements provided in COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016; 

Instruct the OIC-Municipal Accountant to immediately prepare the Disbursement Vouchers for the release of prior year’s payables on RPT shares to the recipient barangays. Moving forward, RPT shares of barangays should be released within five (5) days after the end of each quarter; and

Instruct the Focal Persons to implement immediately and without delay the funded programs of the National Government and other Local Government Units to allow maximized benefits for the programs’ intended recipients.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct the:

HRM Officer to prepare an Organizational Structure and Staffing Pattern Plan, and formulate policies and guidelines so that the necessity and propriety of hiring job order employees are justified;

HRM Officer to strengthen the controls in the hiring of JOs by requiring them to submit personal records, undergo interview, and document performance evaluation to give assurance that the risk identified above is addressed;

Job Order personnel to submit monthly DTRs, and accomplishment reports which are specific as to actual duties performed and deliverables attained to substantiate the payment of wages; and

The Accounting Office to ensure that creditable withholding taxes are deducted from payments for professional fees and the same be remitted to the BIR within the prescribed period.

Recommendations
We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct:
The OIC-Municipal Accountant upon issuance of the Certificate of Final Acceptance for projects, require the contractors the posting of warranty security in the form and amount provided under Section 62.2.3.3 of RA 9184 to guarantee faithful performance of their responsibilities prescribed in Section 62.2.3.1(a) of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184;
The BAC and its Secretariat to submit the lacking documents, as enumerated, to the Audit Team and warrant the completeness of supporting documents that need to be prepared/submitted in the procurement stages of projects in accordance with the provisions of DILG MC No. 2020-088 and RA No. 9184 and its Revised IRR;
The OIC-Municipal Accountant to submit the duly approved notice of time extension and suspension of work, if any, otherwise, impose the payment of liquidated damages to the contractor with delayed project completion in accordance with Section 8, Annex E of RA 9184; and
The OIC-Municipal Accountant to ensure that all necessary documents are attached to the DVs before making the payment/s.

Recommendations
We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to require:
The responsible officers to immediately submit the required documents to avoid suspension of transactions;
The concerned officials/heads of office to ensure compliance with the submission of complete and sufficient supporting papers on all claims against government funds as required under Section 4(6) of PD No. 1445, COA Circular No. 2012-001, and Budget Circular No. 2007-1 so that validity thereof could be properly established and validated;
The OIC-Municipal Accountant to ensure that the payment for honoraria be remitted to the respective mother agencies of government personnel with the corresponding certificates on the taxes withheld and that honoraria paid to resource persons and lecturers are properly computed in accordance with Budget Circular No 2007-1; and
The OIC-Municipal Accountant to ensure that withholding taxes are deducted from payments for honoraria and professional fees, and the same are remitted to the BIR within the prescribed period.

Recommendations
We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to require concerned officials and employees to:
Submit the lacking documents in accordance with Section 3.f, Article A, Chapter XVI of Ordinance No. 2014-06;
Limit the grant of scholarship to poor but deserving students residing within the Municipality and studying in schools located within its jurisdiction in accordance with the mandate of the Local Government Code of 1991;
Enhance the rules and regulations for the Iskolar Kang San Joaquin program to include a provision that financial assistance granted to scholars should be limited to the total amount of tuition and miscellaneous fees due to be paid to the school/university;
Invalidate the scholarships of those grantees who were already college/university scholars in compliance with the relevant provisions stated in Ordinance No. 2014-06; and
Strictly require the submission of proof of enrollment and statements of account / assessment per semester.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE):

Instruct the BAC or duly authorized procuring unit to require the supplier a copy of its Registration Certificate/License to operate as rice dealer/seller issued by the NFA otherwise, provide a justification as to the efficiency of negotiating from the supplier instead of directly negotiating from the NFA or a NFA licensed rice dealer;

Instruct the BAC to provide a justification as to the acceptance of the OSS submitted by the supplier despite the apparent deficiencies noted in the document as well as in the Contract/PO;

Direct the end-user unit to submit a certification stating the type/variety of rice that was received from the supplier; and

Direct the concerned offices to henceforth require the provision of the technical description of items procured in the Contract/PO, Bid Proposals of suppliers and Acceptance and Inspection Report to enable the proper evaluation of bids received and verification of items upon acceptance vis-à-vis the Contract/PO.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct:

The BAC to ensure that a Performance Security in the prescribed form and amount is submitted by the winning bidder before the signing of the contract;

The Municipal Accountant to require the submission of an irrevocable standby letter of credit of equivalent value from a commercial bank, a bank guarantee, or a surety bond callable upon demand, issued by a surety or insurance company duly licensed by the Insurance Commission and confirmed by the procuring entity before advance payment is made; 

The Municipal Accountant to retain the ten percent retention money from payments to every progress billing made by the contractors, subject to the conditions set forth under Section 6 Annex E of the Revised IRR of RA 9184;

The Municipal Accountant to require the submission of duly approved notice of time extension and suspension of work otherwise, impose the payment of liquidated damages to contractors with delayed project completion in accordance with Section 8, Annex E of RA 9184.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the SWMB and concerned offices to:

Hasten the implementation of the projects for the safe closure of the open dump site in accordance with Section 37 of RA No. 9003 and ensure that the objectives of the safe closure and rehabilitation plan is achieved;


Inform and orient the residents near the dumpsite’s vicinity on ordinances issued prohibiting unauthorized entry and scavenging of wastes in the dumpsite;

Provide adequate technical assistance to the personnel in-charge of final sorting of wastes in the MRF and to augment the existing workforce if necessary, to hasten their work and to prevent stack-piling of wastes outside of the RCA and MRF; and

Enhance the capacity of the RCA and MRF as the size of both facilities were inadequate to cater the voluminous wastes transferred thereto for final sorting and storage and/or to look for alternative methods in the disposal of wastes such as purchase of equipment/machinery which incinerates residual wastes so that more space will be available for wastes awaiting final sorting.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct:

The Municipal Accountant to see to it that retention money is withheld before payments are made to contractors and/or ensure that the financial instruments submitted to substitute the retention money are in the form and amount as allowed under Section 6, Annex E of RA 9184 and must meet the conditions stated therein before substitution is allowed;

The BAC to see to it that the contracts entered into by the Municipality as well as the Notices of Award and to Proceed are properly dated and the date of receipt by the winning bidder is properly indicated in the documents so that the reckoning dates and effectivity of the notices will be easy to ascertain;

The Municipal Accountant to impose liquidated damages to contractors with delayed project completion in accordance with Section 8, Annex E of RA 9184;

The Municipal Engineer to ensure that a detailed site investigation/ inspection is conducted prior to the implementation of the projects so as to avoid suspension of construction works for a significant period of time and to enable the timely usage of the projects by the intended recipients; and

The Municipal Engineer to see to it that a warranty security should be issued effective for one year from the date of issuance of the Certificate of Final Acceptance for the projects listed above and should be returned only after the lapse of the said one year period. The posting of warranty security should be in the form and amount provided under Section 62.2.3.3 of RA No. 9184 to guarantee the contractor’s faithful performance of their responsibilities prescribed in Section 62.2.3.1(a) of the Revised IRR of RA No. 9184.

Recommendations
We recommended and the Local Chief Executive agreed to direct:
The BAC to ensure that a Performance Security in the prescribed form and amount is submitted by the winning bidder before the signing of the contract;
The Municipal Accountant to require the submission of an irrevocable standby letter of credit of equivalent value from a commercial bank, a bank guarantee or a surety bond callable upon demand, issued by a surety or insurance company duly licensed by the Insurance Commission and confirmed by the procuring entity before advance payment is made;
The Municipal Accountant to retain the ten percent retention money from payments to every progress billings made by the contractors, subject to the conditions set forth under Section 6 Annex E of the Revised IRR of RA 9184;
The Municipal Accountant to require the submission of duly approved notice of time extension and suspension of work otherwise, impose the payment of liquidated damages to contractors with delayed project completion in accordance with Section 8, Annex E of RA 9184.
The aforementioned audit observation was communicated to management thru Audit Observation Memorandum No. 2021-017 dated March 30, 2021.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

a. Instruct the Municipal Engineer and concerned personnel to look into the causes of the delays of the foregoing projects and make necessary measures to effect their completion;

b. Require the regular and thorough monitoring and supervision of projects to ensure that construction works are accomplished in accordance with the terms of the contract and that only satisfactorily completed projects are paid;

c. Consider rescinding or terminating contracts with negative slippages and impose liquidated damages on the defaulting contractors as appropriate; and

d. Direct the Municipal Accountant to make certain that all supporting documents are complete and properly reviewed for any claims against the contractor before the approval of payments.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Instruct the Municipal Engineer and concerned personnel to look into the causes of the delays of the foregoing projects and make necessary measures to effect their completion;
Require the regular and thorough monitoring and supervision of projects to ensure that construction works are accomplished in accordance with the terms of the contract and that only satisfactorily completed projects are paid;
Consider rescinding or terminating contracts with negative slippages and impose liquidated damages on the defaulting contractors as appropriate; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant to make certain that all supporting documents are complete and properly reviewed for any claims against the contractor before the approval of payments.
